         <center><p>To manage Feline Immunodeficiency Virus (FIV) in cats, it is essential to follow a few key recommendations. Regular veterinary check-ups are crucial for monitoring your cat's health and catching any secondary infections early. Keeping your FIV-positive cat indoors helps reduce exposure to other cats and potential infections. Providing a balanced and nutritious diet supports their immune system, while creating a calm and stress-free environment contributes to their overall well-being. Ensure your cat stays up-to-date on vaccinations and preventative treatments for fleas, ticks, and worms. Good dental hygiene, including regular check-ups and cleanings, is important since dental diseases are common in FIV-positive cats. Address any signs of illness immediately, as these cats are more susceptible to infections. If you have multiple cats, take steps to prevent fights to reduce the risk of deep bite wounds, which can spread FIV. By following these guidelines, you can help ensure a healthier and longer life for your FIV-positive cat.</p> </center>   
